    {"parentUuid":"99502079-a100-45bf-8bcb-ce5b388edb2b","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"bc8aeb42-cb85-4d82-b79a-c44f5ad43ae2","agentId":"a7057a0f76b38cecd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012h2bYE1RrNHtVgdj8fVW8p","type":"tool_result","content":"all_known_exact_formulas.md\narithmetic_pi_formula.md\ncloitre_analytic_recurrence.txt\ncombinatorial_formulas.md\nexact_formulas_research.md\nfinal_search_results.txt\ngap_analysis.md\nimpossible_dream_analysis.txt\nlatest_2026_breakthroughs.md\nlatest_research_2026.md\nnovel_patterns.md\nono_partition_primes.txt\nrecursive_formulas.md\nsession2_breakthrough_analysis.md\nstate_of_the_art_nth_prime.txt\ntg_kernel_details.txt","is_error":false}]},"uuid":"3321b8be-ae18-499a-9122-e92f5d2d1bdf","timestamp":"2026-04-04T05:05:59.278Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"99502079-a100-45bf-8bcb-ce5b388edb2b","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"db81d721-ff28-4a87-9083-507961151cfc","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"idempotent-spinning-forest"}
    {"parentUuid":"3321b8be-ae18-499a-9122-e92f5d2d1bdf","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a7057a0f76b38cecd","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014mBZtQga613yBLG6RswXg3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01YAfjcGtewo4uudHeai8W8A","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/INTERESTING/april_2026_new_findings.md","content":"# New Findings: April 2026 Search Update\n\nCompiled: 2026-04-04\nPrevious: latest_2026_breakthroughs.md (covers through early April 2026)\n\n---\n\n## What Is Genuinely NEW (not in any previous file)\n\n### 1. primecount 8.3 and 8.4 (March-April 2026)\n\n**Source:** https://github.com/kimwalisch/primecount/blob/master/ChangeLog\n\n**primecount 8.4 (2026-04-01):**\n- Branchfree implementation of Gourdon's D formula with SIMD support\n- New AVX512 and ARM SVE SIMD variants of the D algorithm\n- New documentation: \"Hard-Special-Leaves-SIMD-Filtering.pdf\"\n- CPU detection for AVX512BW and AVX512VL instruction sets\n\n**primecount 8.3 (2026-03-16):**\n- Bidirectional clustered easy leaves optimization in S2_easy.cpp and AC.cpp\n- Faster lightweight compression for segmented pi table\n- Improved x64 assembly for fast division (128-bit division on x64)\n- Separated pi and bits lookup tables to avoid interleaving overhead\n- Tuned alpha_z for new AC algorithm\n\n**primecount 8.2 (2026-02-01):**\n- Minor: packaging fix and loop condition refinement in AC algorithm\n\n**Relevance to our project:** The SIMD-accelerated Gourdon D formula in v8.4 is\nsignificant -- it means the hard special leaves computation (the bottleneck in\nDeleglise-Rivat/Gourdon) is now vectorized. This could yield 2-4x speedup on\nmodern CPUs with AVX512. For anyone implementing their own pi(x), the\n\"Hard-Special-Leaves-SIMD-Filtering.pdf\" document could be very instructive.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Gafni-Tao: Exceptional Intervals for PNT in Short Intervals (May 2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv:2505.24017\n**Authors:** Ayla Gafni, Terence Tao\n**Submitted:** May 29, 2025\n\n**Key result:** Provides an explicit quantitative relationship between zero\ndensity estimates and the number of exceptional intervals where the prime\nnumber theorem fails in short intervals [x, x + x^theta].\n\nUsing Guth-Maynard zero density estimates:\n- PNT in short intervals holds for ALL x when theta > 17/30\n- PNT holds for ALMOST ALL x when theta > 2/15\n\nThe paper gives explicit upper bounds on the size of the exceptional set\n(improving Bazzanella-Perelli), with computer-assisted optimization.\n\n**Relevance:** Provides tighter guarantees on prime distribution in short\nintervals. For binary search when computing p(n), this means: for intervals\nof length x^{17/30} around the target, we can guarantee primes exist. This\ncould help tighten binary search bounds slightly, but the practical impact\nis marginal since Visser's exponential bounds already give tight brackets.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Le Duc Hieu: AP of Primes in Short Intervals Beyond 17/30 (Sept 2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv:2509.04883\n**Author:** Le Duc Hieu\n**Submitted:** September 5, 2025 (v2: September 24, 2025)\n\n**Key result:** Once theta > 17/30, every sufficiently long interval\n[x, x + x^theta] contains many k-term arithmetic progressions of primes,\nuniformly in x.\n\n**Method:** Combines the uniform short-interval PNT at exponents theta > 17/30\n(from Guth-Maynard zero density) with the Green-Tao transference principle\n(relative Szemeredi theorem) on a window-aligned W-tricked block.\n\n**Relevance:** Purely theoretical for our project. Confirms the richness of\nprime structure in intervals that are computationally accessible, but does\nnot provide new algorithms for computing p(n).\n\n---\n\n### 4. Lichtman: Modified Linear Sieve, x^{10/17} Equidistribution (Published 2025)\n\n**Source:** Algebra & Number Theory, Volume 19, Number 1 (2025)\n**arXiv:** arXiv:2109.02851 (first submitted 2021, published 2025)\n**Author:** Jared Duker Lichtman\n\n**Key result:** Introduces modified linear sieve weights that equidistribute\nprimes up to size x in arithmetic progressions to moduli up to x^{10/17}.\n\nThis surpasses:\n- x^{4/7} (Bombieri-Friedlander-Iwaniec, classical)\n- x^{7/12} (Maynard's extension, which was the natural barrier)\n\nAs an application: new upper bound on twin prime count, the largest percentage\nimprovement since Bombieri-Friedlander-Iwaniec (1986). Simplifies Wu's 2004\nargument.\n\n**Relevance:** Improved equidistribution of primes in arithmetic progressions\nis fundamental infrastructure. While not directly an algorithm for p(n), it\nshows that sieve methods continue to advance. The x^{10/17} threshold is\nnotable because it breaks past what was thought to be a natural barrier at\nx^{7/12}.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Pascadi: Primes and Smooth Numbers to x^{5/8} (May 2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv:2505.00653\n**Author:** Alexandru Pascadi\n**Submitted:** May 1, 2025 (v2: June 29, 2025)\n\n**Key result:** Both primes and smooth numbers are equidistributed in arithmetic\nprogressions to moduli up to x^{5/8 - o(1)}, using triply-well-factorable\nweights.\n\n**Breakthrough aspect:** Completely eliminates the dependency on Selberg's\neigenvalue conjecture in previous works of Lichtman and the author (which\nbuilt on Maynard and Drappeau). Uses new large sieve inequalities for\nexceptional Maass forms.\n\nApplications include refined upper bounds for twin prime counts and\nconsecutive smooth number counts.\n\n**Relevance:** x^{5/8} = x^{0.625} is very close to the critical exponent\nx^{2/3} ~ x^{0.667} used in Deleglise-Rivat. If equidistribution results\ncould be pushed to x^{2/3}, it might enable algorithmic improvements to\ncombinatorial pi(x) methods. Currently still below that threshold but the\ngap is closing.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Heuristic Zero Density Improvement (Zeraoulia Rafik, 2026)\n\n**Source:** hal-05201671 (HAL preprint, March 2026)\n**Title:** \"From Chaos to Density: A New Algorithm for the Riemann Hypothesis\nvia a Spectral Operator with Rigorous Lyapunov Bounds and Heuristic\nImprovements on the Maynard-Guth Estimate\"\n**Author:** Zeraoulia Rafik\n\n**Key claims:** Computer simulations yield an effective Lyapunov exponent of\napproximately -0.7, resulting in a heuristic zero density estimate that\nimproves upon Guth-Maynard.\n\n**Assessment:** CAUTION -- this is a single-author HAL preprint using\n\"spectral-dynamical\" and \"fractal\" methods. The word \"heuristic\" in the title\nis a red flag: the improvement is not proven, only suggested by numerical\nexperiments. The methodology (chaos theory applied to zero density) is\nunconventional and has not been peer-reviewed. Treat with skepticism until\nverified by the community.\n\n**Relevance:** If the heuristic improvement could be made rigorous, it would\ntighten zero density bounds beyond Guth-Maynard, which could propagate to\nbetter PNT in short intervals. But this is speculative.\n\n---\n\n## Updated Assessment Delta (What Changed Since Last File)\n\n### For computing p(n) directly:\n- **No new algorithms** for computing p(n) or pi(x) with better asymptotic\n  complexity have appeared since the last update.\n- **primecount 8.4** with SIMD Gourdon D formula represents significant\n  practical speedup (constant factor, not asymptotic) for combinatorial pi(x).\n\n### For theoretical understanding:\n- **Gafni-Tao** makes Guth-Maynard results more explicit and quantitative\n  for short intervals.\n- **Lichtman** and **Pascadi** push equidistribution of primes past previous\n  barriers (x^{10/17} and x^{5/8} respectively).\n- **Le Duc Hieu** extends AP-in-short-intervals results using Green-Tao +\n  Guth-Maynard.\n\n### The fundamental barrier remains:\nNo one has published any method to compute p(n) faster than O(n^{1/2+eps})\n(analytic) or O(n^{2/3}/polylog) (combinatorial). The equidistribution\nadvances are closing in on the x^{2/3} threshold used by Deleglise-Rivat\nbut have not reached it, and even if they did, it is unclear whether they\nwould yield algorithmic improvements.\n\n---\n\n## Sources\n\n- [primecount ChangeLog](https://github.com/kimwalisch/primecount/blob/master/ChangeLog)\n- [primecount Releases](https://github.com/kimwalisch/primecount/releases)\n- [Gafni-Tao: Exceptional intervals (arXiv:2505.24017)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.24017)\n- [Le Duc Hieu: AP primes beyond 17/30 (arXiv:2509.04883)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.04883)\n- [Lichtman: Modified linear sieve (arXiv:2109.02851)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2109.02851)\n- [Lichtman: Published version (ANT 2025)](https://msp.org/ant/2025/19-1/ant-v19-n1-p01-p.pdf)\n- [Pascadi: Exponents of distribution (arXiv:2505.00653)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.00653)\n- [Rafik: From Chaos to Density (HAL)](https://hal.science/hal-05201671v1/document)\n- [Guth-Maynard: Published in Annals of Mathematics (2025)](https://annals.math.princeton.edu/articles/22049)\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":451,"cache_read_input_tokens":42770,"output_tokens":2727,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":451},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CZi9cf7ZWpNsqb3pjmWAF","type":"assistant","uuid":"d6b2738e-cac4-47ad-8324-31d1f56fe47f","timestamp":"2026-04-04T05:06:56.636Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"db81d721-ff28-4a87-9083-507961151cfc","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"idempotent-spinning-forest"}
    {"parentUuid":"d6b2738e-cac4-47ad-8324-31d1f56fe47f","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"bc8aeb42-cb85-4d82-b79a-c44f5ad43ae2","agentId":"a7057a0f76b38cecd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YAfjcGtewo4uudHeai8W8A","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/INTERESTING/april_2026_new_findings.md"}]},"uuid":"c03d97ff-ae4c-448a-85d8-223dd8511e0a","timestamp":"2026-04-04T05:06:56.642Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"d6b2738e-cac4-47ad-8324-31d1f56fe47f","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"db81d721-ff28-4a87-9083-507961151cfc","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"idempotent-spinning-forest"}
    {"parentUuid":"c03d97ff-ae4c-448a-85d8-223dd8511e0a","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a7057a0f76b38cecd","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01L4WqEAk9ub1ewVbZrtTzx8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the summary of what was found and what is new.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of New Findings (April 2026 Search)\n\n**Saved to:** `/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/INTERESTING/april_2026_new_findings.md`\n\n### Genuinely New Items (not in any previous file):\n\n1. **primecount 8.3 + 8.4 (March-April 2026)** -- The most practically relevant finding. Version 8.4 introduces a **branchfree SIMD implementation of Gourdon's D formula** (AVX512 and ARM SVE), targeting the hard special leaves bottleneck. This is a meaningful constant-factor speedup for combinatorial pi(x) computation. A new internal document \"Hard-Special-Leaves-SIMD-Filtering.pdf\" was added. Version 8.3 added bidirectional clustered easy leaves and faster compression for the segmented pi table.\n\n2. **Gafni-Tao (May 2025, arXiv:2505.24017)** -- Makes the Guth-Maynard zero density results explicitly quantitative for short intervals. Gives computable upper bounds on the number of exceptional intervals where PNT fails. Useful theoretical infrastructure but no new algorithms.\n\n3. **Le Duc Hieu (Sept 2025, arXiv:2509.04883)** -- Shows that once theta > 17/30, every long interval [x, x+x^theta] contains many k-term arithmetic progressions of primes. Combines Guth-Maynard with Green-Tao. Purely theoretical.\n\n4. **Lichtman (ANT 2025, arXiv:2109.02851)** -- Modified linear sieve weights equidistribute primes to moduli up to **x^{10/17}**, breaking past Maynard's x^{7/12} barrier. New twin prime upper bound -- largest percentage improvement since 1986.\n\n5. **Pascadi (May 2025, arXiv:2505.00653)** -- Primes equidistributed to **x^{5/8}** without Selberg's eigenvalue conjecture. Uses new large sieve inequalities for exceptional Maass forms. This x^{0.625} exponent is approaching the x^{2/3} ~ x^{0.667} threshold of Deleglise-Rivat, which is interesting to watch.\n\n6. **Guth-Maynard published** (Annals of Mathematics, April 2025) -- Their 2024 preprint on zero density was formally accepted. Confirmed as a landmark result.\n\n### What Did NOT Change:\n\n- **No new asymptotic improvement** to computing p(n) or pi(x). The best remains O(n^{1/2+eps}) analytic / O(n^{2/3}/polylog) combinatorial.\n- **No new \"pure formula\"** for the nth prime without implicit sieving.\n- **No progress on the fundamental barrier**: no polynomial-time, non-sieve method for exact p(n).\n- The Platt-Trudgian zeta zero verification record (3 x 10^12) from 2021 still stands -- no new record found.\n\n### What Is Potentially Useful for Your Project:\n\nThe **primecount 8.4 SIMD Gourdon D formula** is the only item with direct practical impact. If you are implementing or optimizing a pi(x) computation, the SIMD filtering technique for hard special leaves could be adapted. The equidistribution advances by Lichtman and Pascadi are worth monitoring -- if they reach x^{2/3}, they might enable theoretical improvements to combinatorial pi(x)."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2768,"cache_read_input_tokens":43221,"output_tokens":880,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2768},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CZi9gtKfbdX4PL28vrNKN","type":"assistant","uuid":"c3fd2191-6570-4db9-b673-f480857fb5a3","timestamp":"2026-04-04T05:07:15.309Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"db81d721-ff28-4a87-9083-507961151cfc","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"idempotent-spinning-forest"}
    
