    --- Comparison: smooth integral vs discrete zeros ---
      n=  100: smooth=101.4150 (err=1.4150), discrete=101.6501 (err=1.6501)
      n=  500: smooth=499.8682 (err=0.1318), discrete=502.1790 (err=2.1790)
      n= 1000: smooth=999.6560 (err=0.3440), discrete=1003.3811 (err=3.3811)
    
    --- CONCLUSION ---
    The smooth zero sum replaces Σ f(γ_k) with ∫ f(t) N'(t) dt.
    If this works, it avoids enumerating zeros entirely!
    But N'(t) misses the oscillatory part S(t), causing errors.
    The oscillatory part S(t) = (1/π) arg ζ(1/2+it) is exactly
    what encodes the irregularity of primes - it cannot be avoided.
Fascinating result! The **smooth zero sum** approach (replacing discrete sum over zeros with integral against N'(t)) actually outperforms using 20 discrete zeros for large n (error 0.13 vs 2.18 at n=500). But errors are still O(1), not consistently < 0.5.

The fundamental issue: the integral requires T ~ √x for error < 1, and the oscillatory integrand needs O(√x) quadrature points. Same O(x^{1/2}) barrier.

