    {"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"0322b342-540a-4dba-84a5-c613553065ba","agentId":"aa067f96adfdc7aeb","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"You are working on finding a formula for the nth prime p(n). Goal: p(10^100) in under 1 second, NO bruteforcing.\n\nYOUR TASK: Run deep computational experiments looking for hidden structure in the prime sequence.\n\n1. **Base representation analysis**: Look at p(n) in bases 2, 3, 6, 30, 210 (primorial bases). Is there a pattern in the digits?\n\n2. **Continued fraction of p(n)/n·ln(n)**: Compute the CF expansion for various n. Are there patterns in the partial quotients?\n\n3. **P-adic properties**: Compute p(n) mod p for small primes p=2,3,5,7,11,... Look for correlations between p(n) mod p and n.\n\n4. **Gap ratios**: Compute g(n)/ln(p(n)) where g(n)=p(n+1)-p(n). Study the distribution. Is it exactly exponential? Any deviations that could help?\n\n5. **Prime gap prediction via Cramér's model**: Generate Cramér random primes and see how well they match real primes statistically. Quantify the deviation.\n\n6. **Autocorrelation of δ(n) at LONG lags**: Previous work looked at r(1)=0.996. Look at r(k) for k=1..1000. Is there a periodic component?\n\n7. **Cross-correlations between δ(n) and number-theoretic functions**: li(p(n))-n, Chebyshev ψ(p(n)), Mertens function M(p(n)), etc.\n\n8. **Can we express p(n) using a SMALL number of precomputed constants?** E.g., if we precompute 100 real constants, can a simple formula using those constants give p(n) exactly?\n\nRun all experiments, report findings.\n\nWrite code to /apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/session6_experiments/deep_structure.py\nWrite results to /apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/session6_experiments/deep_structure_results.md"},"uuid":"4a9777b8-b2d7-4e12-a8bf-38fe2171f1c5","timestamp":"2026-04-04T07:26:25.680Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"f5332890-89d2-40a2-b821-fa5bcff74ef