    # Session 6: Deep Structural Experiments on the Prime Sequence
    
    **Date**: 2026-04-04  
    **Data**: ~970K primes up to 15M  
    **Runtime**: 33.5 seconds  
    
    ---
    
    ## Experiment 1: Base Representation Analysis
    
    Analyzed p(n) in bases 2, 3, 6, 30, 210 and in primorial mixed-radix.
    
    ### Key findings:
    
    | Base | Normalized Entropy | Last-digit classes | Notes |
    |------|-------------------|-------------------|-------|
    | 2 | 0.995 | {1} only | All primes > 2 are odd |
    | 3 | 0.995 | {1, 2} equally | All primes > 3 are non-zero mod 3 |
    | 6 | 0.990 | {1, 5} equally | p ≡ 1 or 5 (mod 6) |
    | 30 | 0.952 | 8 classes, ~12.5% each | Coprime residues mod 30 |
    | 210 | 0.917 | 48 classes, ~2.08% each | Coprime residues mod 210 |
    
    **Primorial mixed-radix**: Position 0 (mod 2) has entropy ~0, position 1 (mod 3) has entropy 0.63, and by position 3 (mod 7) entropy is already 0.999. The structure is purely the coprimality constraint -- no deeper pattern.
    
    **Conclusion**: The digit structure in all bases is explained entirely by the well-known coprimality sieve. No hidden pattern beyond what the prime number theorem and Dirichlet's theorem predict. **Not exploitable for a formula.**
    
