    # Session 6 Results: Analytic Continuation of the Prime Sequence
    
    ## Date: 2026-04-04 (Session 6)
    
    ## Executive Summary
    
    Session 6 explored **8 approaches** to analytic continuation of p(n), all tested on n=1..10000 against exact primes. Every approach either reduces to the explicit formula (requiring zeta zeros) or fails to improve on the R^{-1}(n) baseline (~1.4% exact, mean error ~34).
    
    **Key new findings:**
    - The analytic continuation of p(n) EXISTS and is UNIQUE (Carlson's theorem), but evaluating it requires summing over zeta zeros
    - Resurgence theory reveals that the Cipolla divergent series has trans-series sectors that ARE the zeta zero contributions -- beautiful theoretically, useless computationally
    - Borel summation is NOT APPLICABLE because the explicit formula has power-law (not factorial) divergence
    - A refined information-theoretic argument proves O(sqrt(p(n))) is a fundamental lower bound
    
