    ## Executive Summary
    
    Nine experiments tested whether sparse/adaptive zero selection can reduce the number of zeta zeros needed in the explicit formula from ~sqrt(x) to polylog(x). The results are **mixed but informative**: for moderate x (up to 10^5), matching pursuit and optimal subset selection achieve error < 0.5 with only 1-3 zeros, but this is **not robust** -- it relies on lucky cancellations that become increasingly rare as x grows.
    
