    ---
    
    ## Executive Summary
    
    This session investigates whether the **verification** of "p = p(n)" can be cheaper than
    **computing** it. The answer is a resounding YES -- with an enormous gap between
    computation and verification cost. However, this does not help a solver who must find
    p(n) from scratch.
    
    ### The Central Result
    
    | Operation | Cost for p(10^100) | Feasible in 1 sec? |
    |-----------|-------------------|-------------------|
    | Compute p(n) from scratch | O(10^68) ops | NO (needs 10^59 seconds) |
    | Verify with sieve certificate | O(10^34) ops | NO (needs 10^25 seconds) |
    | Verify with STARK proof | O(10^4) ops | YES (~1 millisecond) |
    | Verify Pratt primality cert | O(10^4) ops | YES (~1 millisecond) |
    
    **Verification is exponentially cheaper than computation**, but someone must do
    the computation first.
    
