    ## Executive Summary
    
    We investigated whether succinct data structures — bit vectors with rank/select, compressed representations (RRR, Elias-Fano), hierarchical tables, learned indexes, precomputed zeta zeros, and correction tables — can achieve O(1) p(n) queries for n up to 10^100.
    
    **The answer is NO**, and the reason is not algorithmic but information-theoretic: the prime sequence below 10^102 contains approximately 4.3 x 10^99 primes, and any data structure that can answer arbitrary p(n) queries must store at least ~10^100 bits. This exceeds the number of atoms in the observable universe (~10^80) by a factor of 10^20. No clever encoding can circumvent this.
    
    ---
    
    ## Information-Theoretic Lower Bound
    
    The minimum storage for ANY data structure supporting p(n) queries for all n in [1, 10^100]:
    
    | Quantity | Value |
