      —     0.0026s     0.0077s\n\nPart B: Relationship between M(x) and pi(x)\n------------------------------------------------------------\nIdentity: pi(x) = sum_{k=1}^{log2(x)} mu(k)/k * Pi(x^{1/k})\nwhere Pi(x) = pi(x) + pi(x^{1/2})/2 + pi(x^{1/3})/3 + ...\n\nBut this uses pi() INSIDE the sum — it's not a shortcut!\n\nAlternative: sum_{n<=x} mu(n)*floor(x/n) = sum_{n<=x} sum_{d|n} mu(d)\n                                         = sum of 1 for squarefree n <= x\n                                         = Q(x) (squarefree counting)\n\nQ(x) = 6x/pi^2 + O(sqrt(x)) — no direct link to pi(x).\n\nPart C: Complexity comparison\n------------------------------------------------------------\nBest known M(x) computation: O(x^{2/3} / (ln x)^{1/3})\n  (Deléglise-Rivat, same as for pi(x))\nBest known pi(x) computation: O(x^{2/3} / (ln x)^{4/3})\n  (Lucy_Hedgehog DP)\n\nVERDICT: M(x) is HARDER to compute than pi(x), not easier.\nThe Mertens function does not provide a shortcut.\n\n>>> Running Experiment 4: Dirichlet Characters\n\n========================================================================\nEXPERIMENT 4: Dirichlet Characters — Modular Reconstruction\n========================================================================\n\nPart A: Prime distribution in arithmetic progressions\n------------------------------------------------------------\nq=  2: residues=1, sum pi(x;q,a)=167, +1 dividing q = 168, pi(1000)=168, match=YES\nq=  3: residues=2, sum pi(x;q,a)=167, +1 dividing q = 168, pi(1000)=168, match=YES\nq=  4: residues=2, sum pi(x;q,a)=167, +1 dividing q = 168, pi(1000)=168, match=YES\nq=  6: residues=2, sum pi(x;q,a)=166, +2 dividing q = 168, pi(1000)=168, match=YES\nq= 12: residues=4, sum pi(x;q,a)=166, +2 dividing q = 168, pi(1000)=168, match=YES\nq= 30: residues=8, sum pi(x;q,a)=165, +3 dividing q = 168, pi(1000)=168, match=YES\n\nPart B: CRT reconstruction analysis\n------------------------------------------------------------\nIdea: Compute pi(x) mod m for many small m, then CRT.\n\npi(x) mod 2 = parity of number of primes up to x\nEven computing pi(x) mod 2 requires knowing whether pi(x) is even/odd\nNo known shortcut for this parity — it's as hard as computing pi(x)\n\nPart C: Structured prime sources\n------------------------------------------------------------\nPrimes of the form n^2 + 1: 2, 5, 17, 37, 101, 197, ...\nFound 19 primes of form n^2+1 for n <= 100:\n  First 10: [2, 5, 17, 37, 101, 197, 257, 401, 577, 677]\n\nBateman-Horn predicts #{p=n^2+1, n<=N} ~ C * N / ln(N)\nBut testing each n^2+1 for primality still costs O(polylog(n)) per test,\nand there are O(N/ln N) primes, so total O(N * polylog(N) / ln(N)).\nTo find p(n), we still need to enumerate — no direct formula for the k-th\nprime of a given form.\n\nVERDICT: Modular decomposition doesn't help.\nComputing pi(x; q, a) has the SAME complexity as pi(x).\nThe information content is the same; we're just partitioning it.\n\n>>> Running Experiment 5: Selberg Zeta\n\n========================================================================\nEXPERIMENT 5: Selberg Zeta / Geodesic Primes\n========================================================================\n\nPart A: Geodesic norms from PSL(2,Z) traces\n------------------------------------------------------------\nTraces and their geodesic norms:\n trace                 norm     ln(norm)  is_int?\n     3     6.85410196624968     1.924847       no\n     4     13.9282032302755     2.633916       no\n     5     22.9564392373896     3.133598       no\n     6     33.9705627484771     3.525494       no\n     7     46.9787137637478     3.849695       no\n     8     61.9838667696593     4.126874       no\n     9     78.9873397432645     4.369288       no\n    10     97.9897948556636     4.584863       no\n    11     118.991596045156     4.779053       no\n    12     141.992957397195     4.955777       no\n    13     166.994011761323     5.117958       no\n    14     193.994845223857     5.267832       no\n    15     22