===========\nSESSION 8 SUMMARY: Novel Encoding Approaches\n========================================================================\nTotal runtime: 2.4s\n\nEXPERIMENT VERDICTS:\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n1. Prime Zeta P(s) extraction:     FAIL — needs s~n, cost O(poly(n))\n2. Ramanujan R(x) rounding:         PARTIAL — works for small x only\n   Error grows as O(x^{1/2}), rounding fails around x ~ 10^7\n   Correcting with zeta zeros costs O(x^{1/2+eps}) — same barrier\n3. Mertens M(x):                    FAIL — same O(x^{2/3}) as pi(x)\n4. Dirichlet characters mod q:       FAIL — same complexity, just partitioned\n5. Selberg zeta / geodesics:         FAIL — encodes different objects entirely\n6. Information theory:               CONFIRMS barrier at ~0.53*log2(p(n)) bits\n\nKEY INSIGHT FROM THIS SESSION:\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nAll 5 analytic approaches encode THE SAME information in different forms.\nThe prime zeta function, Ramanujan R, Mertens, Dirichlet L-functions,\nand the explicit formula with zeta zeros are all EQUIVALENT representations.\nThey are connected by Mobius inversion, Mellin transforms, and spectral theory.\n\nSwitching representation cannot reduce complexity because the underlying\ninformation content is invariant: ~0.53 * log2(p(n)) bits of 'prime randomness'\nthat no deterministic O(polylog n) procedure can produce.\n\nThe Selberg zeta (Exp 5) is the only genuinely DIFFERENT object,\nbut it encodes geodesic primes, not integer primes. Its own prime\ngeodesic theorem has the same O(x^{2/3+eps}) barrier.\n\nREMAINING HOPE: If primes have hidden algebraic structure (e.g., a\nrecursive formula for prime gaps), it could compress the 180 missing bits.\nBut 200+ years of number theory has found no such structure.\n\nSTATUS: 210+ approaches tried. All confirm the barrier.\nThe O(x^{2/3}) complexity appears to be a FUNDAMENTAL LIMIT.","is_error":false}]},"uu