    {"parentUuid":"ce2519ee-b8ca-4bbf-b1b4-c15b148b8f7f","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a878899143c899ceb","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01FD3pdnuWMDFFzDZ9Y1Rshf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01TWpKLdoC5Y73AjAK5z7v1D","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"python3 session9_experiments/interpolation_attack.py 2>&1","timeout":120000},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11152,"cache_read_input_tokens":12459,"output_tokens":107,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":11152},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CZifPA9QtmwbvqG5jQNCN","type":"assistant","uuid":"f7f9a37c-c53c-474b-806e-49dcfaebdaff","timestamp":"2026-04-04T11:36:25.724Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"0542525e-41e3-4b9e-b6e3-27a1e5e0c3a7","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"cached-honking-squid"}
    
    === aa1f60d7d927f4878.output ===
    {"parentUuid":"9dec9a7c-22e8-47e0-b9b3-a4d3ced4f066","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa1f60d7d927f4878","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Vbbup3u36ihtqnsVR6aiQv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_019mPDmdmWoAnVXvMqfVN1Fu","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/INTERESTING/session9_new_findings.md","content":"# Session 9: Internet Search Results (2026-04-04)\n\nPrevious sessions covered: Aggarwal, Guth-Maynard, Ono partition detection,\nCloitre recurrence, Prunescu-Shunia arithmetic terms, Harper Gaussian chaos,\nGafni-Tao, Lichtman, Pascadi, primecount 8.2-8.4, Visser bounds, Bouras GCD,\nGoldston-Lee-Schettler-Suriajaya pair correlation, Green-Sawhney p^2+4q^2,\nVettori density framework, Partial Vandiver (arXiv:2602.05090), AxiomProver,\nBotkin et al. partition model, Le Duc Hieu AP in short intervals, Rafik\nheuristic zero density, Harman sieve refinement, sum of two almost primes.\n\nThis file documents NEW findings not covered in any previous session file.\n\n---\n\n## MAJOR NEW ITEMS\n\n### 1. Alain Connes: \"The Riemann Hypothesis: Past, Present and a Letter Through Time\" (February 2026)\n\n**Source:** [arXiv:2602.04022](https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.04022)\n**Author:** Alain Connes\n**Submitted:** February 3, 2026\n\n**Key new contribution -- \"Letter to Riemann\":**\nConnes introduces a method inspired by Riemann's own approach to the conformal\nmapping theorem. By extremizing a restriction of Weil's quadratic form, he\nobtains remarkable approximations to zeros of zeta.\n\n**Striking result:** Using only primes less than 13, this optimization procedure\nyields approximations to the first 50 nontrivial zeros of zeta with accuracies\nranging from 2.6 x 10^{-55} to 10^{-3}. Moreover, it is proven that these\napproximating values lie EXACTLY on the critical line Re(s) = 1/2.\n\n**Significance:**\n- Establishes a deep connection between Weil's quadratic form and information\n  theory\n- Develops a geometric perspective using trace formulas\n- Outlines a potential proof strategy for RH based on establishing convergence\n  of zeros from finite to infinite Euler products\n- The extremization approach is novel and could represent a new tool for\n  studying zeta zeros\n\n**Assessment:** This is a major survey + new contribution from one of the most\nimportant living mathematicians working on RH. The \"Letter to Riemann\" section\ncontains genuinely new mathematics. However, a full proof of RH remains elusive;\nthe convergence argument is outlined but not completed.\n\n**Relevance to nth prime:** Indirect but significant. If the finite Euler product\napproximation method can be made constructive, it could potentially yield new\nways to approximate pi(x) using only small primes -- conceptually similar to\nwhat our project attempts.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Ran Raz: Natural Proofs for Super-Linear Lower Bounds on Linear Functions (January 2026)\n\n**Source:** [ECCC TR26-008](https://eccc.weizmann.ac.il/report/2026/008/)\n**Author:** Ran Raz\n**Date:** January 20, 2026\n\n**Key result:** Extends Razborov-Rudich natural proofs framework to the context\nof proving circuit lower bounds for linear functions A: F^n -> F^n over finite\nfields.\n\nConsiders both Boolean circuits and arithmetic circuits with scalar products\nand sum gates over F. Formally defines when a lower bound proof for the circuit\ncomplexity of a linear function is \"natural\" -- if for every n it defines a\npolynomial-time recognizable subset C'_n of all linear functions comprising at\nleast a polynomial fraction, and the lower bound holds for every function in\nC'_n.\n\n**Significance:** This is the first formalization of natural proof barriers\nspecifically for linear circuit complexity. Shows what approaches CANNOT work\nfor proving super-linear lower bounds, guiding future research.\n\n**Relevance to nth prime:** Tangential but relevant to our impossibility analysis.\nIf arithmetic circuit lower bounds for linear functions face natural proof\nbarriers, this constrains what kind of \"shortcut\" formulas for p(n) can be\nproven to not exist.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Chen-Tal-Wang: Super-Quadratic Lower Bounds for Depth-2 Linear Threshold Circuits (March 2026)\n\n**Source:** [ECCC TR26-039](https://eccc.weizmann.ac.il/report/2026/039/)\n**Authors:** Lijie Chen, Avishay Tal, Yichuan Wang\n**Date:** March 15, 2026\n\n**Key result:** There exists a function in E^NP that requires n^{2.5-epsilon}-size\nTHR-of-THR circuits for any epsilon > 0.\n\n**Method:** Designs a new 2^{n - n^{Omega(epsilon)}}-time algorithm for estimating\nthe acceptance probability of an XOR of two n^{2.5-epsilon}-size THR-of-THR\ncircuits, then applies Williams' algorithmic method.\n\n**Significance:** THR-of-THR (depth-2 linear threshold circuits) is a frontier\nin circuit complexity. This is the strongest known lower bound for this model.\n\n**Relevance to nth prime:** Relevant to our impossibility analysis. Depth-2\nthreshold circuits are a powerful model; showing they cannot compute certain\nfunctions efficiently constrains what simple formulas can accomplish.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Tao-Teravainen: Quantitative Correlations on Prime Factors of Consecutive Integers (December 2025)\n\n**Source:** [arXiv:2512.01739](https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.01739)\n**Authors:** Terence Tao, Joni Teravainen\n**Submitted:** December 1, 2025\n\n**Key results:**\n- Proves an Erdos-Straus conjecture: infinitely many n where omega(n+k) <= k\n- Proves irrationality of sum omega(n)/2^n (Erdos conjecture)\n- Proves asymptotic formula conjectured by Erdos-Pomerance-Sarkozy for\n  consecutive integers with equal prime divisor counts\n\n**Method:** Probabilistic method combined with high-dimensional Maynard-type\nsieve, plus quantitative two-point correlation estimates for multiplicative\nfunctions with logarithmic savings.\n\n**Relevance to nth prime:** Indirect. Shows new quantitative control over prime\nfactor statistics of consecutive integers. Does not yield algorithms for p(n)\nbut deepens understanding of prime distribution structure.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Tao: \"Products of Consecutive Integers with Unusual Anatomy\" (March 2026)\n\n**Source:** [arXiv (March 31, 2026)](https://terrytao.wordpress.com/)\n**Author:** Terence Tao\n\n**Key result:** Answers questions of Erdos and Graham motivated by the Diophantine\nfactorial equation. Confirms an Erdos-Graham conjecture in two cases, comes\nclose in the third. Involves bounds on numbers lying in \"bad intervals\" related\nto the factorial equation.\n\n**Methods:** Prime number theorem, zero density estimates, Vinogradov's bounds on\nexponential sums, asymptotics for smooth numbers, large sieve, fundamental\nlemma of sieve theory, Burgess bound for character sums.\n\n**Relevance to nth prime:** Indirect. Uses many of the same tools that underpin\npi(x) computation theory, but the results are about multiplicative structure\nof consecutive integers rather than prime enumeration.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Tao: \"Local Bernstein Theory, and Lower Bounds for Lebesgue Constants\" (March 2026)\n\n**Source:** [arXiv (March 23, 2026)](https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2026/03/23/local-bernstein-theory-and-lower-bounds-for-lebesgue-constants/)\n**Author:** Terence Tao\n\n**Key significance -- AI co-authorship milestone:**\nThis paper contains a key inequality whose proof was generated by ChatGPT.\nTao reduced the problem to a toy inequality, ChatGPT identified it as an\napproximation theory question and produced a duality-based proof built on the\nFourier expansion of the square wave. The matching lower bound resisted\nChatGPT and was solved by Tao with contour integrals and the residue theorem.\n\n**Assessment:** This is one of the first instances of a Fields Medalist\npublishing a paper where an AI model contributed a non-trivial proof step\nin a research-level result. While the paper itself is about interpolation\ntheory (not primes), the methodology precedent is significant.\n\n---\n\n## NEW PAPERS (2026) -- PRIME NUMBER THEORY\n\n### 7. Bailleul-Hayani-Untrau: Wasserstein Approach to Generalized Skewes Numbers (March 2026)\n\n**Source:** [arXiv:2603.20093](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.20093)\n**Authors:** Alexandre Bailleul, Mounir Hayani, Theo Untrau\n**Submitted:** March 20, 2026\n\n**Key results:**\n- Constructs sequences of highly composite moduli where Skewes numbers (first\n  sign change between comparable prime counting functions) grow very rapidly\n- Unconditionally disproves a conjecture of Fiorilli\n- Assuming GRH + effective linear independence, establishes conditional upper\n  bounds for generalized Skewes numbers\n- Uses quantitative Kronecker-Weyl theorem formulated in terms of 1-Wasserstein\n  metric for explicit convergence rates\n\n**Relevance to nth prime:** Relevant to understanding prime number races and\nwhere pi(x) exceeds Li(x). Novel use of optimal transport (Wasserstein metric)\nin analytic number theory.\n\n---\n\n### 8. Volfson: Generalization of Hardy-Littlewood Conjecture to Almost-Prime Tuples (March 2026)\n\n**Source:** [arXiv:2603.13416](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.13416)\n**Author:** Victor Volfson\n**Submitted:** March 12, 2026\n\n**Key contributions:**\n- Extends Hardy-Littlewood k-tuple conjecture to tuples of almost-prime numbers\n- Proposed asymptotic formula: density = Selberg constant x correction factor\n- Proves admissibility of patterns for primes implies admissibility for almost-primes\n- Establishes symmetry principle: correction factor depends on multiset of\n  requirements, not on order within tuple\n- Develops empirical-analytical method for computing correction factor based on\n  invariance of Selberg constant under pattern stretching\n\n**Relevance to nth prime:** Extends fundamental conjectures about prime\ndistribution to almost-primes, but does not provide new algorithms.\n\n---\n\n### 9. Hakobyan: \"Almost Prime Numbers\" -- New Generalization (February 2026)\n\n**Source:** [arXiv:2603.00679](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.00679)\n**Author:** Tigran Hakobyan\n**Submitted:** February 28, 2026\n\n**Key result:** Introduces a new concept of \"almost prime number\" generalizing\nprimality. Shows that a composite almost prime number must be a Carmichael\nnumber (if it exists). Proves several properties and conjectures infinitude\nof composite almost primes.\n\n---\n\n### 10. Vartziotis: Fourier Series from Additive Prime Factor Functions (February 2026)\n\n**Source:** [arXiv:2602.13342](https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.13342)\n**Author:** Dimitris Vartziotis\n**Submitted:** February 12, 2026\n\n**Key contributions:**\n- Constructs sparse prime-indexed Fourier series using sopfr(n) (sum of prime\n  factors with multiplicity) and its summatory function B(x) ~ pi^2 x^2/(12 log x)\n- Establishes exact prime-indexed decomposition of B(n)\n- Relates construction to circulant Hermitian polygon transformations whose\n  eigenpolygons are discrete Fourier modes\n- Proves precise norm identities connecting arithmetic and analytic structures\n\n**See also:** arXiv:2602.21270 -- \"Rigorous Geometric Obstructions for Fourier\nCurves Generated by Prime Numbers\" (companion paper)\n\n**Relevance to nth prime:** Connects prime factorization statistics to Fourier\nanalysis. Interesting structural result but not algorithmic.\n\n---\n\n### 11. Li: Deterministic Fractal Set from Prime Number Sequence (February 2026)\n\n**Source:** [arXiv:2603.00658](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.00658)\n**Author:** Zhengqiang Li\n**Submitted:** February 28, 2026\n\n**Key result:** Constructs a deterministic Cantor-like fractal set PF in [0,1]\ndriven by primes mod 16. Each recursive step retains two subintervals based on\nconsecutive prime residues. Proves PF is non-empty, compact, nowhere dense, with\nLebesgue measure zero and Hausdorff dimension = box-counting dimension = 1/4.\n\n**Notable:** The dimension 1/4 is UNIVERSAL -- depends only on branching number\n(2) and contraction ratio (1/16), not on the specific prime residue sequence.\n\n---\n\n### 12. Li (Runbo): Prime-Producing Sieves and Distribution of alpha*p - beta mod 1 (April 2025, revised October 2025)\n\n**Source:** [arXiv:2504.13195](https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.13195)\n**Author:** Run
