    # Session 9: Zeta Zero Compressibility Analysis - Results
    
    ## Executive Summary
    
    **The zeta zero sum is NOT compressible to O(polylog x).**
    
    The fundamental barrier is a **phase sensitivity catastrophe**: even though the Backlund smooth approximation gives gamma_n to ~3 digits, the oscillatory sum S(x) = sum_rho R(x^rho) requires gamma_n to approximately (D/2) digits for x ~ 10^D. For p(10^100), we need each of ~10^47 zeros known to ~49 digits. No compression scheme can bypass this because the required information scales as O(sqrt(x) * log(x)) bits.
    
    ---
    
    ## 1. Residual Structure: gamma_n - gamma_n^{smooth}
    
    The Backlund approximation gamma_n^{smooth} is obtained by inverting
    N(T) = (T/2pi) * log(T/2pie) + 7/8.
    
    ### Statistics (N=1000 zeros)
    
    | Metric | Value |
    |--------|-------|
    | Mean residual | -0.704 (systematic bias) |
    | Std of residuals | 0.409 |
    | Max |residual| | 3.713 |
    | Range | [-3.713, +0.264] |
    | Mean digits from smooth | 3.06 |
    | Min digits from smooth | 0.58 |
    
    **Key finding**: The smooth approximation provides only ~3 correct digits of gamma_n. For the first 1000 zeros (gamma ~ 14 to 1420), the zeros have ~3 digits total, so the smooth part gives roughly half the information. For higher zeros (gamma_n ~ 2*pi*n/log(n)), the number of digits grows as log(n) while the residual stays O(1), so the fraction of information from the smooth part increases slowly.
    
