    # Computational Complexity of the Prime Counting Function pi(x)
    
    **Date:** 2026-04-04
    **Research question:** Can pi(x) be computed in polylogarithmic time? What are the theoretical limits?
    
    ---
    
    ## 1. KNOWN UPPER BOUNDS (Algorithms for Computing pi(x))
    
    ### 1.1 Combinatorial Methods
    
    | Algorithm | Time Complexity | Space Complexity | Year |
    |-----------|----------------|-----------------|------|
    | Sieve of Eratosthenes | O(x log log x) | O(x) | Ancient |
    | Legendre | O(x) | O(sqrt(x)) | 1808 |
    | Meissel | O(x/(log x)^3) | -- | 1870-1885 |
    | Meissel-Lehmer | O(x/(log x)^4) | O(x^(1/3)/log x) | 1959 |
    | Lagarias-Miller-Odlyzko (LMO) | O(x^(2/3)/log x) | O(x^(1/3)) | 1985 |
    | Deleglise-Rivat | O(x^(2/3)/log^2 x) | O(x^(1/3) log^3 x log log x) | 1996 |
    | Gourdon | O(x^(2/3)/log^2 x) | O(x^(2/3) log^3 x) | 2001 |
    
    **Current best combinatorial: O(x^(2/3) / log^2 x)**
    
    ### 1.2 Analytic Methods
    
    | Algorithm | Time Complexity | Space Complexity | Year |
    |-----------|----------------|-----------------|------|
    | Lagarias-Odlyzko (analytic) | O(x^(1/2+epsilon)) | O(x^(1/4+epsilon)) | 1987 |
    | Lagarias-Odlyzko (space-efficient) | O(x^(3/5+epsilon)) | O(x^epsilon) | 1987 |
    
