    **THIS IS THE CRITICAL GAP:** There are NO known super-logarithmic
    unconditional lower bounds for computing pi(x).
    
    The gap between the best upper bound O(x^(1/2+eps)) and the trivial
    lower bound Omega(log x) is ENORMOUS. No one has proved that computing
    pi(x) requires more than O(log x) time. This is an open problem.
    
    ### 2.4 Why Lower Bounds Are Hard
    
    Proving lower bounds for natural computational problems is one of the
    hardest tasks in complexity theory. We cannot even prove that SAT
    requires more than linear time (unconditionally). The barriers to
    proving lower bounds (relativization, natural proofs, algebrization)
    apply broadly.
    
    ---
    
    ## 3. COMPLEXITY CLASS RESULTS
    
    ### 3.1 Primality Testing (PRIMES = "Is n prime?")
    
    This is a DECISION problem about individual numbers, distinct from computing
    pi(x). But it provides important context.
    
    **Known results:**
    - PRIMES is in P (AKS, 2002) -- deterministic polynomial time O~((log n)^6)
    - PRIMES is in coRP (Miller-Rabin) -- randomized polynomial time
    - PRIMES is in RNC -- randomized NC (Miller-Rabin parallelizes)
    - PRIMES is NOT in AC^0 (known unconditionally)
    - PRIMES is NOT in AC^0[p] for any prime p (Allender, Saks, Shparlinski)
