    same situation applies to computing pi(x) from binary input.
    
    ### 4.3 Model B: Unary Input -- Sublinear Computation
    
    In the unary input model (or equivalently, measuring complexity in terms
    of x rather than log x):
    - O(x^(1/2+eps)) is the best known (Lagarias-Odlyzko analytic)
    - O(x^(2/3)/log^2 x) is the best known combinatorial
    - The O(sqrt(x)) barrier seems deep -- it relates to the distribution
      of zeta function zeros
    
    **Key barrier:** The analytic method fundamentally needs to evaluate
    sums over zeta zeros up to height ~x^(1/2), and there are ~(T/2pi)log(T/2pi)
    zeros up to height T. This creates an apparent omega(x^(1/2)) barrier
    for analytic methods.
    
    The combinatorial methods seem to face an O(x^(2/3)) barrier related
    to the need to evaluate partial sieve functions.
    
    ### 4.4 Connection to the Riemann Hypothesis
    
    Under RH, the error in the prime number theorem is O(x^(1/2) log x).
    But this gives an APPROXIMATION, not the exact count.
    
    To compute pi(x) EXACTLY using the analytic approach, one needs
    information about zeta zeros, which connects to the difficulty of
    the Riemann zeta function itself.
    
